pullRequest.body:
This extends the simple attribute of #16179 with an environment extension that tracks also the declaration names and tags.

The `#stacks_tags` command retrieves all declarations that have the `stacks` attribute.

For each found declaration, it prints a line
```
'declaration_name' corresponds to tag 'declaration_tag'.
```
The variant `#stacks_tags!` also adds the theorem statement after each summary line.

[Zulip thread](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/113488-general/topic/stacks.20tags)

---

Matt, thanks for the review!  I should have taken care of cleaning up the left-overs!
Do we need this?
No, this is a left-over from a previous attempt: I removed it!

This is a bit ambiguous from the name. I think most people would guess it returns the tags sorted by the stack project tag, like the master list on the stacks project repo. 

I'm guessing there will be more querying using the stacks project tag than the name of the registered declaration so adding a function here to do that would nice also.

Ok, I'll rename to `Lean.Environment.getSortedStackProjectTags`.

The second comment is about creating a function that takes a (string) "tag" as input and returns an `Option Name`?

I think you should just switch to returning the `Stacks.Tag`s sorted by the `tag` rather than `declName`. 

The second comment was about a ~~`Lean.Environment.findStacksTag`~~ `CoreM Name` function which indeed returned an `Option Name` and consumed the string Stacks project tag.
Ok, great!  I'll return an `Array Name`, since conceivably the same Stacks tag could be applied to multiple lemmas, if they each prove a part of the Stacks result.
I just pushed both changes.
Uh oh. Are we keeping track of the comments at all?
I thought that the comments would be discarded: should the `Stacks.Tag` record them as well?
Yeah, I think that was why Kim asked for them. To record discrepancies between the two statements.
Comments added!
